kMohammed Bobat, of Azaadville Muslim School, got distinctions for all seven of his subjects. Although it sounded like a clich&eacute;, discipline and hard work were the keys to success, he said.&ldquo;It&rsquo;s all about controlling yourself the whole year. There are many reasons not to work, but to be successful is a reason to work hard.&ldquo;I had to cut down on relaxation time, going out with friends, TV time, and I had to study more in the late nights and early mornings.&rdquo;#GPNSC2016 Some of Gauteng's Top Achievers. pic.twitter.com/ofx3U6edZ5&mdash; Mpho Raborife (@MsRaborife) January 5, 2017#GPNSC2016 Some of Gauteng's Top Achievers. pic.twitter.com/ofx3U6edZ5What helped Faadhil Kolia, of Lenasia Muslim School, get seven As was applying subjects such as Maths and Science beyond the classroom.&ldquo;I found that Mathematics is actually the language of nature. It&rsquo;s a way in which we humans have synthesised a language in order to describe the symmetry that we see everywhere. So they should look at subjects in these ways, as a means of learning and satisfying your curiosity.&rdquo;Sacrificing time with friends was necessary to ensure a successful academic year, he said.Six-A matric Sulaiman Saloojee, of Roshnee Islamic School in Vereeniging, echoed his point.&ldquo;Work hard. Don&rsquo;t be distracted by anything because your future depends on this year,&rdquo; he said.Kholofelo Mohale, of Realogile High School in Alexandra, got distinctions in all seven of her subjects and 100% for Mathematics. She urged the class of 2017 to do some introspection and find the best study methods.They had to know their work front to back and ask their teachers to explain anything they did not understand, she said.Do more than what is expectedGizelle Venske, who also got a full house of distinctions at Ho&euml;rskool Transvalia in Vanderbijlpark, said her secret was to always do more than expected.&ldquo;You always have to do more than what is required of you and I think the key to success here is to be a well-balanced student, not only focus on your academics, but also take on some other activities as well.&rdquo;Malebo Leshabane, of Botsebotse High School in Soshanguve, urged those who had not done so well to follow their own path and resist succumbing to peer pressure.&ldquo;Just work hard, don&rsquo;t give up. Just say &lsquo;I am an individual and I&rsquo;m going to work hard to do what I want to do&rsquo;.&ldquo;Not all of us are academics. Find yourself. Don&rsquo;t force yourself to be like another person who got those distinctions. Just try to find out, &lsquo;who am I?&rsquo; You are a star to yourself and you a star in something else.&rdquo;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.